<br>
With out you (to combine), he has nothing.<br>
With out him (to supply the materials), you have nothing.<br>
<br>
Once its reduced to this, its all about haggling a mutually agreeable profit for both.<br>
<br>
What stuck in my Craw, as it were, was the &quot;I am a GM, YOU SHALL BOW TO ME&quot; attitude.  F' that.  You spent your time your way, I spent mine my way.<br>
<br>
Also, any mention of &quot;all the past millions of plat I spent GMing this skill!&quot; bugs me.  I infer (right, or wrongly) from the way EQ tradeskills were primarly designed, that they were a &quot;Forsooth, I have looted a passel of spider silks, I think I shall try to make a robe to cover my filthy body!  Curses, failed again.  No worries, for there are other fish in the sea.  Have at ye, A_Young_Kodiak_36!&quot;  If you skill up off of what you hunt/aquire through yourself or your friends, costs are rather low.  Its only when you Blitz a skill that you pay the price in cash rather than time, The example of ornate chain vs. FS plate comes to mind.<br>
<br>
I don't know one tradeskiller, who after tallying all his costs and profits, finds he's broke even, proceeds to do all combines for free for the rest of his life.  This mythical GM is the only person I'd respect a &quot;I spent X and need to make it back!&quot; line from.<br>
<br>
As for a rebuke to Anduran about Macroquest.  I'll respect that you probably are more in touch with the &quot;tradeskills scene&quot; than I am.  But How hard is Miss Cleo to setup?  And how many people use that?  You can't tell me that Setting up Macroquest is any harder.  Hell, even limiting the combines to 40-50 a min (down from the stupidly obvious 15 combines a second), using eather all store bought recipies, or just making sure you have materials for several hundred combines at a go, its still quick and painless.<br>
<br>
JC: Macroable to GM off storebought stuff.<br>
Pottery: Macroable to GM off storebought stuff.<br>
Baking: (assuming you have pottery high enough) Macroable to GM off storebought stuff.<br>
Brewing: Macroable to GM off storebought stuff.<br>
Smithing: Macroable to high 200's off storebought stuff.<br>
Tailoring: Macroable to low 200's  off storebought stuff.<br>
Poison: Macroable to GM off storebought stuff.<br>
Alchemy: Macroable to GM off storebought stuff.<br>
Archery: Macroable to GM off storebought stuff.<br>
(my numbers are pulled from my own head, and may be off a tad; I've got a lot of crap up here!)<br>
<br>
All it takes is Plat, and time to set your macros up.  Hell, the more you micromanage your macros, the less this method takes beyond what you'd spend by hand.  And no more wristpain at the thought of 9 item combines.<br>
<br>
Now, I'm not saying Macroquest and the like are right.  But, just as I assume that Warrior that just beat the ranger/bard hydra in my party to Quillmane is using Miss Cleo, I'll Assume that any GM has saved thier wrists and wits, and macroed it.<br>
<br>
Ninen of Saryrn<br>
